views.text: Appendicitis is acute inflammation of the vermiform appendix, typically resulting in abdominal pain, anorexia, and abdominal tenderness. Diagnosis is clinical, often supplemented by CT or ultrasonography. Treatment is surgical removal of the appendix.
views.desc: <button bound_box=60,900,1020,1620>Appendicitis is acute inflammation of the vermifor</button>

views.text: In the United States, acute appendicitis is the most common cause of acute abdominal pain requiring surgery. Over 5% of the population develops appendicitis at some point. It most commonly occurs in adolescence and in the 20s but may occur at any age.

views.text: Other conditions affecting the appendix include carcinoids, cancer, villous adenomas, and diverticula. The appendix may also be affected by
views.desc: <button bound_box=60,1623,1002,1626>Other conditions affecting the appendix include ca</button>

views.text: Appendicitis is thought to result from obstruction of the appendiceal lumen, typically by lymphoid hyperplasia but occasionally by a fecalith, foreign body, tumor, or even worms. The obstruction leads to distention, bacterial overgrowth, ischemia, and inflammation. If untreated, necrosis, gangrene, and perforation occur. If the perforation is contained by the omentum, an appendiceal abscess results.
views.desc: <button bound_box=60,1623,1020,1626>Appendicitis is thought to result from obstruction</button>
<button bound_box=0,1623,1080,1626>   Symptoms and Signs of Appendicitis</button>

views.text: The classic acute appendicitis symptoms are
views.desc: <button bound_box=60,1623,1020,1626>The classic acute appendicitis symptoms are</button>

views.text: Epigastric or periumbilical pain followed by brief nausea, vomiting, and anorexia
views.desc: <button bound_box=180,1623,999,1626>Epigastric or periumbilical pain followed by brief</button>

views.text: After a few hours, the pain shifts to the right lower quadrant. Pain increases with cough and motion.
views.desc: <button bound_box=60,1623,1020,1626>After a few hours, the pain shifts to the right lo</button>

views.text: Right lower quadrant direct and rebound tenderness located at the McBurney point (junction of the middle and outer thirds of the line joining the umbilicus to the anterior superior iliac spine)
views.desc: <button bound_box=180,1623,1005,1626>Right lower quadrant direct and rebound tenderness</button>

views.text: Additional appendicitis signs are pain felt in the right lower quadrant with palpation of the left lower quadrant (Rovsing sign), an increase in pain caused by passive extension of the right hip joint that stretches the iliopsoas muscle (psoas sign), or pain caused by passive internal rotation of the flexed thigh (obturator sign).
views.desc: <button bound_box=60,1623,1020,1626>Additional appendicitis signs are pain felt in the</button>

views.text: Low-grade fever (rectal temperature 37.7 to 38.3°C [100 to 101° F]) is common.

Many variations of appendicitis symptoms and signs occur in > 50% of patients. Pain may not be localized, particularly in infants and children. Tenderness may be diffuse or, in rare instances, absent. Bowel movements are usually less frequent or absent; if diarrhea is a sign, a retrocecal appendix should be suspected. Red or white blood cells may be present in the urine.
views.desc: <button bound_box=60,1623,1020,1626>Many variations of appendicitis symptoms and signs</button>

views.text: Atypical symptoms are common among older patients and pregnant women; in particular, pain is less severe and local tenderness is less marked.
views.desc: <button bound_box=60,1623,1020,1626>Atypical symptoms are common among older patients </button>

views.text: When classic appendicitis symptoms and signs are present, the appendicitis diagnosis is clinical. In such patients, delaying appendicitis surgery to do imaging tests only increases the likelihood of perforation and subsequent complications.
views.desc: <button bound_box=60,1623,1020,1626>When classic appendicitis symptoms and signs are p</button>

views.text: In patients with atypical or equivocal findings, imaging studies should be done without delay. Contrast-enhanced CT has reasonable accuracy in diagnosing appendicitis and can also reveal other causes of an acute abdomen. Graded compression ultrasonography can usually be done quickly and uses no radiation (of particular concern in children); however, it is occasionally limited by the presence of bowel gas and is less useful for recognizing nonappendiceal causes of pain.
views.desc: <button bound_box=60,1623,1020,1626>In patients with atypical or equivocal findings, i</button>

views.text: Appendicitis remains primarily a clinical diagnosis. Selective and judicious use of imaging studies may reduce the rate of negative laparotomy.
views.desc: <button bound_box=60,1623,1020,1626>Appendicitis remains primarily a clinical diagnosi</button>

views.text: Laparoscopy can be used for diagnosis as well as definitive treatment of appendicitis; it may be especially helpful in women with lower abdominal pain of unclear etiology. Laboratory studies typically show leukocytosis (12,000 to 15,000/mcL [12.00 to 15.00 × 109/L]), but this finding is highly variable; a normal white blood cell count should not be used to exclude appendicitis.
views.desc: <button bound_box=60,1623,1020,1626>Laparoscopy can be used for diagnosis as well as d</button>

views.text: Treatment of acute appendicitis is open or laparoscopic appendectomy. Because treatment delay increases mortality, a negative appendectomy rate of 15% is considered acceptable.
views.desc: <button bound_box=60,1623,1020,1626>Treatment of acute appendicitis is open or laparos</button>

views.text: The surgeon can usually remove the appendix even if perforated. Occasionally, the appendix is difficult to locate. In these cases, it usually lies behind the cecum or the ileum and mesentery of the right colon.
views.desc: <button bound_box=60,1623,1020,1626>The surgeon can usually remove the appendix even i</button>

views.text: A contraindication to appendectomy is inflammatory bowel disease involving the cecum. However, in cases of terminal ileitis and a normal cecum, the appendix should be removed.

views.text: When a large inflammatory mass is found involving the appendix, terminal ileum, and cecum, resection of the entire mass and ileocolostomy are preferable. In late cases in which a pericolic abscess has already formed, the abscess is drained either by an ultrasound-guided percutaneous catheter or by open operation (with appendectomy to follow at a later date).

views.text: Without surgery or antibiotics, the mortality rate for appendicitis is > 50%.
views.desc: <button bound_box=60,1623,1020,1626>Without surgery or antibiotics, the mortality rate</button>

views.text: With early surgery, the mortality rate is < 1%, and convalescence is normally rapid and complete.
